 {"id": "franken_networkx-nxgraph", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] Cross-library constructor drops edges \u2014 fnx.Graph(nx.Graph) returns empty", "description": "fnx.Graph(nx.path_graph(3)) silently returned an empty graph because the Rust __new__ only knows fnx own graph types \u2014 for foreign (nx) graph instances it copies nodes but not edges. Fix: extend _init_absorbing_dict_of_dicts to detect foreign-graph sources and manually populate edges (with Multi*/simple collapse semantics per br-xmginit). fnx-native same-family sources still skip to avoid double-adding.", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T07:07:28.042006Z", "close_reason": "Fixed in cycle-6.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T07:07:28.042006Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T07:07:28.042006Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-atlascp", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] AtlasView.copy() missing \u2014 breaks nx.to_dict_of_dicts on fnx graphs", "description": "nx.convert.to_dict_of_dicts does nbrdict.copy() on the adj value (which is fnx.AtlasView). AtlasView lacked the .copy() method, so the call crashed with AttributeError. Fix: add copy() returning a plain dict snapshot with attr dicts also materialized.", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T07:07:28.042006Z", "close_reason": "Fixed in cycle-6.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T07:07:28.042006Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T07:07:28.042006Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-edgesnb", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] G.edges(single_node) raises TypeError; nx.line_graph breaks on fnx", "description": "nx.EdgeView accepts a single node as nbunch (yielding edges incident to that node). The Rust edge_view_call expected only None or an iterable, so G.edges(0) raised TypeError: int object is not iterable. This broke nx.line_graph(fnx_graph) because its internal _lg_undirected helper calls G.edges(u) with single nodes. Fix in _edge_view_call_with_nbunch_first: detect non-iterable nbunch via try/except and wrap in a list; also wrap bare str/bytes (iterable per Python but single nodes in nx).", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T07:20:36.456800Z", "close_reason": "Fixed: single-node nbunch now normalized to [nbunch] before hitting the Rust call. 4 regression tests in TestEdgeViewSingleNodeNbunch cover int / str nbunch and end-to-end nx.line_graph on fnx.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T07:20:36.456800Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T07:20:36.456800Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-edgesu1", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] G.edges(u) canonicalizes (min, max) \u2014 breaks nx.degree_assortativity_coefficient on fnx", "description": "nx contract: G.edges(u) yields tuples with the queried node first (`G.edges(3) -> [(3, 2)]`). fnx's Rust EdgeView canonicalizes to (min, max), so G.edges(3) returned [(2, 3)]. This broke nx internals like degree_assortativity_coefficient / node_degree_xy that do `for _, nbr in G.edges(u)` \u2014 they got u itself as nbr instead of the neighbor, producing wildly wrong assortativity values (+0.34 vs the correct -0.71). Fix in _edge_view_call_with_nbunch_first: when nbunch is a single node or iterable, reorder each returned (u, v) tuple so the endpoint in nbunch comes first.", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T07:26:21.239941Z", "close_reason": "Fixed: tuple reorder in _edge_view_call_with_nbunch_first puts the nbunch endpoint first. 3 regression tests in TestEdgeViewNbunchOrdering cover single-node query, list-nbunch query, and nx.degree_assortativity_coefficient end-to-end on fnx.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T07:26:21.239941Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T07:26:21.239941Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
